"de Arce Crespo J.I., Gutiérrez D.","Altitudinal trends in the phenology of butterflies in a mountainous area in central spain",2011,"European Journal of Entomology","108","4",,"651","658",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84858969359&partnerID=40&md5=9b6ba36d4ea2f8eb0be2e1c399f36ebf","C/Pintor Zuloaga 18, Bargas, Toledo, ES-45593, Spain; Área de Biodiversidad y Conservación, Escuela Superior de Ciencias Experimentales y Tecnología, Universidad Rey Juan Carlos, Tulipán s/n, Móstoles, Madrid, ES-28933, Spain","de Arce Crespo, J.I., C/Pintor Zuloaga 18, Bargas, Toledo, ES-45593, Spain; Gutiérrez, D., Área de Biodiversidad y Conservación, Escuela Superior de Ciencias Experimentales y Tecnología, Universidad Rey Juan Carlos, Tulipán s/n, Móstoles, Madrid, ES-28933, Spain","One of the best documented effects of climate change on biodiversity are shifts in phenology. However, long-term data quantifying and projecting the expected changes in phenology associated with climate warming are limited to a few well-recorded areas in the world. In the absence of temporal recording, an alternative approach is to determine the phenological response of species along marked gradients in climate or along latitudinal or altitudinal transects (space-for-time substitution). We studied the phenology (timing and duration of the flight period) of butterflies in 2006 along an altitudinal gradient (900-1680 m; estimated temperature lapse rate = -6.6°C/km) in the Serranía de Cuenca (central Spain) at the assemblage and individual species levels. Timing of the flight period was later for assemblages at high than at low altitudes. A similar trend of an increasing delay in the flight period with altitude was recorded for some individual species. However, there were also some exceptions to this pattern regardless of the number of sites and the altitudinal ranges of the species, suggesting possible local adaptation to regional climate. The duration of the flight period was shorter at high altitudes for assemblages, but this trend was not mirrored in the response of individual species. The results partly support substituting space-for-time when assessing the potential effect of climate change on phenophases such as the timing of the flight period, but we recommend extreme caution in extrapolating the results in the absence of information on how the responses of populations differ.","Butterflies; Duration of the flight period; Elevation; Phenology; Serranía de cuenca; Timing of the flight period","altitudinal zonation; biodiversity; butterfly; climate change; climate effect; ecosystem response; flight activity; flight behavior; global warming; latitudinal gradient; mountain region; phenology; trend analysis; Castilla-La Mancha; Serrania de Cuenca; Spain; Papilionoidea",,,,,,"Alonso Otero, F., La Serranía de Cuenca (1998) Guía de Los Espacios Naturales de Castilla-La Mancha, pp. 265-281. , Junta de Comunidades de Castilla-La Mancha (ed.), Servicio de Publicaciones Consejería de Educación y Cultura de Castilla-La Mancha, Toledo; Ashton, S., Gutiérrez, D., Wilson, R.J., Effects of temperature and elevation on habitat use by a rare mountain butterfly: implications for species responses to climate change (2009) Ecol. Entomol., 34, pp. 437-446; Bale, J.S., Masters, G.J., Hodkinson, I.D., Awmack, C., Bezemer, M., Brown, V.K., Butterfield, J., Whittaker, J.B., Herbivory in global climate change research: direct effects of rising temperature on insect herbivores (2002) Global Change Biol., 8, pp. 1-16; Blionis, G.J., Halley, J.M., Vokou, D., Flowering phenology of Campanula on Mt Olympos, Greece (2001) Ecography, 24, pp. 696-706; Brakefield, P.M., Geographical variability in, and temperatura effects on, the phenology of Maniola jurtina and Pyronia tithonus (Lepidoptera, Satyrinae) in England and Wales (1987) Ecol. Entomol., 12, pp. 139-148; De Arce Crespo, J.I., Jiménez Mendoza, S., Martín Cano, J., Ampliación de la información sobre la distribución 